# [SRV6OPS](../wg/srv6ops.html)

## Summary
The SRV6OPS session at IETF 125 focused on operational experiences and deployment case studies from major network operators. The session included a status update on working group drafts, a discussion regarding a liaison from ITU-T Study Group 11, and three technical presentations covering SRv6 applications in AI cloud computing, security resource pools, and power grid communications. The chairs emphasized the importance of translating these operational experiences into contributions for the active working group documents.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Status and Liaison
*   **Draft Status:** The chairs noted two active adopted drafts:
    *   [draft-ietf-srv6ops-srv6-deployment](https://datatracker.ietf.org/drafts/draft-ietf-srv6ops-srv6-deployment)
    *   [draft-ietf-srv6ops-problem-summary](https://datatracker.ietf.org/drafts/draft-ietf-srv6ops-problem-summary)
*   **ITU-T Liaison:** The group discussed a liaison from ITU-T Study Group 11 regarding SRv6 conformance testing. The chairs noted that IETF has provided feedback previously regarding the distinction (or lack thereof) between "core" and "optional" extensions. Currently, the WG plans no formal action, but individuals are encouraged to review the conformance test cases and reach out to the chairs or the ITU-T liaison (Scott Mansfield) if they believe a group response is necessary.
*   **Presentation:** [1. Introduction](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-srv6ops-1-introduction-00)

### IPv6 & SRv6 in AI Computing (Alibaba)
*   **Presenter:** Trenfei (Alibaba Cloud)
*   **Presentation:** [2.1 IPv6&SRv6 Powering Alibaba Cloud AI Computing (Alibaba)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-srv6ops-21-ipv6srv6-powering-alibaba-cloud-ai-computing-alibaba-02)
*   **Technical Details:**
    *   Alibaba highlighted challenges in AI computing: IPv4 exhaustion, virtualization overhead (VXLAN latency/packet overhead impacting RDMA), and cross-region bandwidth contention.
    *   **NetPillar:** An SRv6-based container network using the SRv6 Best Effort (BE) model within data centers to avoid VXLAN overhead. It leverages a /64 prefix per host for programmability and achieves network isolation by matching Tenant IDs within the IPv6 address fields.
    *   **E-Call:** An SRv6-based backbone network that uses Flow Labels to map traffic to specific paths (RDMA, high bandwidth, or low cost).
    *   **Results:** Deployment across 14+ clusters (90,000+ servers) resulted in a 10% reduction in latency and a 2% increase in throughput.
*   **Discussion:** A question was raised regarding the control plane. Trenfei explained that a centralized network management system pushes mapping information to the "NetPillar" agent on servers, which then selects the appropriate Flow Label based on container requirements.

### SRv6-Driven Security Resource Pools (China Mobile)
*   **Presenter:** Jiaming (China Mobile)
*   **Presentation:** [2.2 SRv6-Driven Security Resource Pools （China Mobile）V1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-srv6ops-22-srv6-driven-security-resource-pools-china-mobilev1-00)
*   **Technical Details:**
    *   Traditional security resource pools rely on Policy-Based Routing (PBR) and VLANs, leading to scalability issues and "traffic tromboning" (inefficient bandwidth use at the gateway).
    *   The SRv6-based approach uses Service Function Chaining (SFC). The Security Gateway (SACGW) acts as the SRv6 Head-end, encapsulating packets with a SID list that steers traffic through various Value-Added Services (VAS) like Firewalls or IPS.
    *   **Efficiency:** For a chain with two VAS nodes, SRv6 showed 200G forwarding performance compared to 15G under PBR, primarily due to reduced link hair-pinning.
*   **Discussion:** Future work includes improving reliability (granularity of failure detection at the VAS level) and exploring Compressed SIDs (C-SID) to reduce header overhead as segment lists grow.

### SRv6 for End-to-End Services (Guangdong Power Grid)
*   **Presenter:** Lu Jian (Guangdong Power Grid)
*   **Presentation:** [2.3. SRv6 for End-to-End Services (Guangdong Power Grid)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-srv6ops-23-srv6-for-end-to-end-services-guangdong-power-grid-01)
*   **Technical Details:**
    *   Guangdong Power Grid is migrating its integrated data network from IP/MPLS to SRv6 across a multi-vendor, multi-area environment.
    *   **Unified NMS:** To manage complexity, they use a hierarchical management structure where a Unified Network Management System (NMS) coordinates with vendor-specific controllers.
    *   **Use Cases:** Simplified VPN deployment for video conferencing with real-time path optimization and "Application-enabled networking" using IDs to map traffic from Smart Grid endpoints (running Harmony OS) to specific SRv6 policies.
*   **Discussion:** 
    *   Mishuan (Huawei) inquired about standardized interfaces. Lu Jian confirmed they use IETF standards like the L3NM (Layer 3 Network Model) for the Northbound Interface, with some custom extensions for specific grid requirements.
    *   A clarification was made regarding latency metrics for video services, noting they monitor both path health and end-to-end service metrics.

